","Wales":"Wales","of Gwynfe,Llangadog Fawr,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1214–":"about 1214–Deceased","1214–Male":"1214–Deceased","1216–Female":"1216–Deceased","1240–Female":"1240–Deceased","1245–Female":"1245–Deceased","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","1200–Female":"1200–Deceased","about 1260":"about 1260","1216":"1216","1214":"1214","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","ABT    1240":"about 1240","about 1214":"about 1214","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1170":"1170","Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Gwynfe, Llangadock, Carmarthen, Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","of Gwynfe,Llangadog Fawr,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Jacques, Andre, Marcel, Pierre, Leonce, Normand, Camille, Lucien, Gilles, Henri.","English, French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, and Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The Middle English forms were <i>Richard</i> and <i>Rikard</i>, respectively Parisian Old French and Old Picard pronunciations of the ancient Germanic name. Middle English <i>Rikard</i> gives rise to the pet form   Rick  , whilst <i>Richard</i> has given the pet forms   Richie   and   Rich  . Both produced rhyming pet forms,   Dick   and   Hick   for <i>Rikard</i> and   Hitch   for <i>Richard</i>.","History: The LA Richard families are mainly descended from Acadian refugees in the second half of the 18th century. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Recker","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from a variant of the personal name   Richard  . This surname is very rare in East Frisia.","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>recke</i> ‘stretch, route, hedge’, or a habitational name for someone from Recke, near Osnabrück."]},{"name":"Ricard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Andre, Armand, Normand, Raoul, Adelard, Adrien, Amedee, Damien, Fernand, Francois, Germaine.","French: variant of   Richard  . Compare   Recor  ,   Record  ,   Recore  , and   Ricord  .","Channel Islands (Guernsey): variant of   Rickard  , the characteristic Norman pronunciation of <i>Richard</i>."]},{"name":"Ricardo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Roberto, Carlos, Angel, Jorge, Ramon, Ediberto, Guillermo, Joaquin, Juana.","Potuguese and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Ricardo</i>, an equivalent of   Richard  .","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the name in 1 above at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."]},{"name":"Rick","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire and Lincolnshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Rick</i>, a pet form of   Richard  . Compare   Rich   2.","German: from a short form of any of the ancient Germanic personal names formed with <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’.","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>ri(c)k</i> ‘enclosed land, fence’, or from <i>reke</i> ‘row, strip of trees’."]},{"name":"Riccardo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Salvatore, Angelo, Vito, Antonio, Carmine, Domenico, Francesca.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Riccardo</i>, an equivalent of   Richard  ."]},{"name":"Pritchard","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Rhisiart</i> ‘son of Richard’(see   Richard  )."]},{"name":"Reick","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Helmuth.","German:","from a medieval personal name, a short form of   Richard  , or less commonly of some other compound name with this first element."]},{"name":"Reichard","meanings":["German: from an ancient Germanic personal name (see   Richard  ). This surname (and its variants) has also been adopted by Jews."]},{"name":"Reisert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Mathias.","German: variant of <b>Reissert</b>, a variant of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ricohard</i> (see   Richard  )."]},{"name":"Reitz","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place near Stolpe in Pomerania called Reitz.","German: from a late medieval pet form of the personal name   Richard   or <i>Heinrich</i> (see   Henry  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Raytse</i>, of ancient Germanic origin."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maredudd ap Richard was born about 1214, in Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales, his father, Richard ap Maredudd, was 46 and his mother, Joan ferch Richard, was 16. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Gwladus ferch Meurig."},"et":{"about 1214–":"umbes 1214–Surnud","1214–Male":"1214–Surnud","1216–Female":"1216–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1216":"1216","1214":"1214","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","ABT    1240":"umbes 1240","about 1214":"umbes 1214","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1170":"1170","Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Gwynfe, Llangadock, Carmarthen, Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","of Gwynfe,Llangadog Fawr,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1214–":"noin 1214–Kuollut","1214–Male":"1214–Kuollut","1216–Female":"1216–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–